        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/430552876?book_show_action=true">Oct 08, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chadwick" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chadwick" href="/user/show/157567-chadwick">Chadwick</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780575077348" href="/book/show/707304.Life_During_Wartime">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/157567-chadwick?shelf=sf">sf</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/157567-chadwick?shelf=war-fiction">war-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer430552876" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1191735262406149810">This is set in a near future where the Cold War has spilled over into an amorphous hot war in Latin America, but at its heart it&apos;s a fever dream retelling of the United States&apos; imperialistic adventures in the territories to the south. Drug-addicted super-soldiers gone feral, psychic assassins, computers that believe themselves to be God, and installation artists who work in warzones are the characters that unravel across the fabric of the book. There are lengthy passages that I am still not cert</span>
  <span id="freeText1191735262406149810" style="display:none">This is set in a near future where the Cold War has spilled over into an amorphous hot war in Latin America, but at its heart it's a fever dream retelling of the United States' imperialistic adventures in the territories to the south. Drug-addicted super-soldiers gone feral, psychic assassins, computers that believe themselves to be God, and installation artists who work in warzones are the characters that unravel across the fabric of the book. There are lengthy passages that I am still not certain if they are mean to be hallucinations experienced by the main character or not, and the very Borgesian work of a mysterious author gives a metafictional texture to much of the book. Beautiful.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1191735262406149810" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


