  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2316064383" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2316064383" />
    <a title="Stephane" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/76436730-stephane"><img alt="Stephane" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1563113233p2/76436730.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2316064383?book_show_action=true">May 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephane" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephane" href="/user/show/76436730-stephane">Stephane</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/76436730-stephane?shelf=united-states">united-states</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/76436730-stephane?shelf=1980-89">1980-89</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/76436730-stephane?shelf=read-in-2020">read-in-2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/76436730-stephane?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/76436730-stephane?shelf=military-sf">military-sf</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/76436730-stephane?shelf=owned">owned</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2316064383" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11756111097112054149">Lucius Shepard<br/>Life in Wartime<br/><br/>Life in Wartime is (mostly, but not exclusively...) a war story, a SF version of <i>Apocalypse Now</i>. Some people link this novel to Philip K. Dick; probably because it becomes hard to decipher what is real and what is a drug-fueled hallucination. The drugs, a touch of magical realism and the fact that the protagonist is essentially a psychic, conspire to give the novel a sort of misty aura. Mood as character. <br/><br/><b>The good</b><br/><br/>Many scenes across the book are quite memorable. If Sh</span>
  <span id="freeText11756111097112054149" style="display:none">Lucius Shepard<br />Life in Wartime<br /><br />Life in Wartime is (mostly, but not exclusively...) a war story, a SF version of <i>Apocalypse Now</i>. Some people link this novel to Philip K. Dick; probably because it becomes hard to decipher what is real and what is a drug-fueled hallucination. The drugs, a touch of magical realism and the fact that the protagonist is essentially a psychic, conspire to give the novel a sort of misty aura. Mood as character. <br /><br /><b>The good</b><br /><br />Many scenes across the book are quite memorable. If Shepard’s goal was to show the war in all its glorious violence and absurdity, he succeeded. You cannot help but feel terrible for the characters, endlessly fed powerful drugs to sharpen their aggression and dull their remorse, and turned into empty shelf in the process. Human beings becoming tools in a conflict they do not understand, with drugs as their gasoline; madness as a coping mechanism and senseless brutality all around. It is a terrible picture. <br /><br />The true nature of the war is never fully fleshed out. We know it is fought in Central America, we know in involves American solider and a timeless feud between two families, the Sotomayors and the Madradas. As to who exactly is fighting who, and why… we are mostly left in the dark. There are references to Afghanistan, Tel Aviv and United Fruits scattered throughout. Perhaps Shepard miss out on a occasion to offer a more pointed social commentary, but I think that leaving this part out also adds a layer of confusion and irrationality to the whole. If the soldiers don’t know why they are fighting, why should we? <br /><br />The prose is at time remarkable. Shepard is a very atmospheric writer, even if there are perhaps too many descriptive passages. When he is successful, he makes you feel like you are travelling rather than reading. As I put the book down, I have a vivid impression of the settings, as if I was there myself. <br /><br /><b>The</b> (somewhat) <b>bad</b><br /><br />The first part of the book was an award winning short story (it won the Hugo, I believe…) It is a great story that Shepard decided to develop into a full length novel. The final work still bears the mark of its origin. It feels a little choppy, like a patchwork of scenes more than a fully integrated narrative. It is not necessarily a bad thing, though. <br /><br />Still, transitions in the novel can be confusing. Let us remember that we are dealing with drugged up psychic soldiers; they are able to project feeling in other’s mind, to influence their thought patterns. They can send enough fear to kill an enemy, adjust the atmosphere of a room to create mayhem, chaos... and, David Mingolla, the protagonist, happens to be particularly powerful. Sometimes, we aren’t so sure if it’s the drugs, the reality (of the novel) or a projection in the future that David is experiencing. Shepard does not exactly help you out either, with some blurry transitions, merging the edge of a scene with the next in an unstructured fashion. I had to return to previous passages at time, only to figure out how we got where we were. <br /><br />Its not bad, but because of my stupid idea of structuring my review around the title of that Eastwood's flick I have to put this here. <br /><br /><b>The</b> (not quite) <b>ugly</b><br /><br />The novel is quite long, too long indeed. Shepard’s prose, at times, seems to get away from him. As I said previously, some scenes are simply magnificent and exquisitely written… and then followed by unnecessarily long-winded detours and <i>complexifications</i>. Was Shepard paid by the words? Cut 75-100 pages of the book, the pace would pick up tremendously and you would end up with a better reading experience.<br /><br />********<br /><br />If you are looking for a noble war story of courage, look elsewhere. If you are looking for a hero who rises above the fray, who bravely distinguish himself in the face of conflict, who stares at the enemy with vigor and sacrifices himself for a greater cause… well this is not it either. But, for those seeking a unique treatment of war in fiction, it might be worth your time. It is not just a war story, its also a love story, a self-discovery journey but war is, in the story, and it articulates everything, just as I suppose a real conflict zone might feel.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11756111097112054149" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


